#include <stack>
#include <vector>

struct ListNode {
    int val;
    ListNode* next;
    ListNode(int x) : val(x), next(NULL) {}
};

std::vector<int> nextGreaterNodes(ListNode* head) {
    std::vector<int> result;
    std::stack<int> greater;
    while (head) {
        while (!greater.empty() && greater.top() < head->val) {
            greater.top() = head->val;
            greater.pop();
        }
        result.push_back(head->val);
        greater.push(0);
        head = head->next;
    }
    return result;
}
```

The algorithm starts by initializing an empty vector to store the results and an empty stack to keep track of the indices of the nodes. Then it iterates through the linked list using the given head. At each node, it compares the top of the stack to the current node's value. If the top of the stack is smaller than the current node's value, the top of the stack will be replaced with the current node's value and the stack will be popped. It will continue doing this until the condition is no longer satisfied or the stack is empty. The value of the current node is then added to the results vector and the index of the latest value that was added gets pushed to the stack. Finally, the algorithm checks if the stack is not empty; if it isn't, the top of the stack will be set to 0 and the stack will be popped. The results vector is then returned. This algorithm works the same way across all four languages, with the only differences being in the syntax and the specific data structures used.

